hew, 1574 in   IGI   (Nantwich, Cheshire), suggests the possibility that it is an irregular variant of   Walthew  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Walthew","meanings":["English: relationship name from the Middle English personal name  <i>Walthef</i>,  <i>Waldef</i>,  <i>Walthew</i>,  <i>Wallef</i> (Old English  <i>Wælþēof</i>, an anglicized form of Old Scandinavian  <i>Valþiófr</i>). The personal name is mostly recorded in N England and the N Midlands. For the name in Scotland,  see  Waldie  .  See also  Wallett  ,   Whattoff  ."]},{"name":"IGI","meanings":["1  English: (i) perhaps a variant of   Garth   with loss of  <i>-r-</i> before the final consonant. Compare Thomas Gath, 1600, John Garth, 1619 in   IGI   (Saint Keyne, Cornwall); Nicholas Gath, 1716, Thomas Garth, 1726 in   IGI   (Saint Breward, Cornwall). (ii) alternatively, a variant of   Goth   with unrounding of the vowel, if not vice versa.","2  Irish: from  <b>Mag Eochadha</b>,  see  McGough  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Warhall was born in 1278, in England, United Kingdom, his father, Sir Thomas Warhall, was 28 and his mother, Lady Frances Mallory, was 26. He had at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"1278–":"1278–Surnud","1278–Male":"1278–Surnud","1302–1365":"1302–1365","1250–Male":"1250–Surnud","1252–1293":"1252–1293","1302":"1302","1278":"1278","1267":"1267","1365":"1365","1252":"1252","1250":"1250","1293":"1293","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1278–":"1278–Kuollut","1278–Mal